Thatâ€™s exactly the right instinct â€” and itâ€™s the single point that every disciplined senior underwriter struggles with when looking at Auto1â€™s structure.

Youâ€™re essentially asking:

â€œIf the structure is bankruptcy-remote and Auto1 is meant to fund CarCoâ€™s costs while solvent, why does the Issuerâ€™s own waterfall (which belongs to senior creditors) need to cover CarCo-level taxes and operational payments at all?â€

Letâ€™s unpack that fully â€” legally, operationally, and from a credit-logic perspective â€” to see why the drafting ended up that way, and whether itâ€™s structurally justified or not.

â¸»

ğŸ§© 1ï¸âƒ£ What the documentation actually does

Under the MDCTA waterfall, before the Issuer pays Senior Interest, it can release funds from:
	â€¢	the Trade-Tax Reserve,
	â€¢	the VAT Reserve, and
	â€¢	the Senior Reserve Account,
to fund CarCo Taxes, Servicer Fees and other senior operational costs.

Those payments are not Issuer liabilities. They are CarCo statutory and operating obligations â€” VAT, trade tax, and costs of keeping the inventory saleable.

So yes â€” from a purist securitisation viewpoint, this is an upstream leakage.

â¸»

âš–ï¸ 2ï¸âƒ£ Why the drafters made this choice

There are three structural reasons:

A. Rating-agency continuity requirement

Both S&P and Scope insisted that, post-Auto1 default, the transaction must continue operating long enough to sell the existing inventory and repay the notes without external cash.
To do that, CarCo still has to:
	â€¢	pay VAT on sales,
	â€¢	remit trade tax,
	â€¢	pay agents, storage, transport, and minor registration fees.

If those canâ€™t be paid, youâ€™d end up with frozen collateral (cars unsold, VAT blocked, tax liens).

Therefore, the Issuerâ€™s reserves act as a secured liquidity bridge to keep CarCo alive just long enough for an orderly run-off.

â¸»

B. Legal separability and bankruptcy remoteness

Auto1â€™s intercompany support is not a guarantee and dies on its insolvency.
The transaction cannot rely on Auto1 paying those costs.
If the structure had required CarCo to wait for external funds, a German administrator could argue that the securitised assets were still operationally dependent on Auto1 and therefore not truly segregated.

By letting the Issuer advance the money from its own pledged reserves (under Trustee control), you eliminate legal dependency on Auto1.

â¸»

C. Tax-authority priority and enforcement risk

German and local tax authorities have preferential claims that outrank secured creditors.
If VAT or trade tax go unpaid, they can place liens on inventory or block sales.
From a senior-credit perspective, using a few million of reserve liquidity to settle tax prevents a potentially catastrophic priority fight.

So the Issuer waterfall pre-funds these to preserve collateral value â€” not to subsidise Auto1, but to keep the collateral free of encumbrances.

â¸»

ğŸ§® 3ï¸âƒ£ Why this feels uncomfortable to a senior lender

From a credit doctrine standpoint, youâ€™re right:

Senior secured liquidity should serve debt service, not borrower operations.

However, Auto1â€™s structure sits between secured lending and asset-based funding:
	â€¢	The â€œborrowerâ€ (CarCo) is the operating entity that realises value.
	â€¢	Without paying those taxes/fees, liquidation stops and recovery collapses.

So the reserves fund those items only to the extent necessary to protect the asset base.
Theyâ€™re more like administrative expenses of the collateral (analogous to trustee or servicer fees in an RMBS) than ongoing business overhead.

â¸»

ğŸ§  4ï¸âƒ£ How to explain this internally

You can articulate it like this to Credit Committee:

â€œWhile the waterfall allows Issuer liquidity to cover CarCoâ€™s tax and operational costs, this is not leakage to Auto1.
These payments are ring-fenced, transaction-related obligations required to preserve and monetise the collateral during run-off.
The structure is designed to survive with no Auto1 support; therefore, reserves fund statutory and essential costs under Trustee control.
Economically, this is equivalent to paying trustee or servicer fees senior in a traditional ABS waterfall.â€

â¸»

ğŸ§± 5ï¸âƒ£ How to make it safer / what to verify
	1.	Tight definition of payable items
Ensure â€œCarCo Taxes and Feesâ€ covers only VAT, trade tax, and costs essential to inventory sale â€” not general operating expenses or corporate overhead.
	2.	Cap reserve draw
Confirm that the maximum draw on the Senior or Trade-Tax Reserve is limited to its predefined target amount.
	3.	Automatic top-up logic
Verify that reserve replenishment occurs only from excess spread or junior proceeds, never by reducing senior principal.
	4.	Post-event control
The Security Trustee should authorise disbursement after Auto1 default â€” not CarCo management.
	5.	Disclosure clarity
When presenting internally, classify these payments as transaction-level maintenance costs, not borrower subsidies.

â¸»

âœ… 6ï¸âƒ£ Bottom line

Perspective	Description
Economic reality	CarCoâ€™s taxes and critical operating costs must be paid to keep collateral marketable.
