Thatâ€™s a great and very advanced question â€” and it goes right to the core of how liquidity protection, sponsor alignment, and inter-company funding interact in Auto1â€™s structure.

Letâ€™s unpack it clearly.

â¸»

ğŸ§© 1ï¸âƒ£ What actually happens when thereâ€™s a deficiency

When the CarCo Deficiency Amount is determined (i.e. available CarCo funds are insufficient to meet the waterfall obligations),
â†’ the Servicer and Security Agent retain or trap those funds inside the structure.
No distributions (like intercompany payments to Auto1 Group) are allowed until the deficiency is cured.

However, this does not mean the Issuer isnâ€™t paid.
It just means the funding chain shifts from â€œexternal flowâ€ to â€œinternal accountingâ€ for that period.

â¸»

ğŸ—ï¸ 2ï¸âƒ£ The structure is designed to isolate the shortfall at CarCo, not starve the Issuer

Letâ€™s recall the chain:

Dealer â†’ CarCo â†’ Issuer â†’ Investors
	â€¢	The Issuer lends to CarCo under the Senior Loan Agreement (and possibly a Mezz Loan).
	â€¢	The Issuer itself funds those loans by issuing notes to investors.
	â€¢	When CarCo sells cars and receives cash, it repays the Issuer according to the CarCo waterfall â†’ Issuer waterfall â†’ investors.

When there is a CarCo deficiency, what happens is:
	â€¢	CarCo doesnâ€™t have enough immediate sales proceeds to pay the full due amount to the Issuer (principal, interest, reserves).
	â€¢	That unpaid portion is recorded as a CarCo Deficiency Amount.
	â€¢	The Issuer recognises a receivable from CarCo â€” an amount due but not yet settled.

So economically:

ğŸ“’ The Issuer is owed the amount (it accrues in its ledger), but itâ€™s not yet funded by cash from CarCo.

â¸»

ğŸ’¡ 3ï¸âƒ£ How the Issuer still meets its own obligations

The Issuerâ€™s obligations (to noteholders) are funded from available Issuer collections, not strictly from a single CarCo transfer on that day.

There are several structural cushions ensuring the Issuer still pays investors even if CarCo is temporarily short:

a. Liquidity Reserve
	â€¢	Funded at ~1 % of senior notes.
	â€¢	Specifically sized to cover at least one month of senior interest and fees.
	â€¢	Drawn to pay timely interest when inflows from CarCo lag.
	â€¢	Replenished before any residual distribution once cash catches up.

b. Overcollateralisation (OC) buffer
	â€¢	The OC built up over time means that even if CarCoâ€™s remittance is lower, the Issuerâ€™s assets (the loan receivable + cash) still exceed note liabilities.
	â€¢	OC ensures thereâ€™s no immediate need for investor cash flow disruption.

c. CarCo Intercompany Support
	â€¢	Under the Framework Contribution Agreement, Auto1 Group may make a Framework Contribution to CarCo to cure a deficiency â€” essentially upstreaming corporate liquidity to avoid persistence of shortfalls.
	â€¢	This is not a guarantee, but in practice it reflects sponsor alignment and ensures operational continuity.

â¸»

ğŸ’° 4ï¸âƒ£ How it flows through the waterfalls

At CarCo level
	1.	Collections from vehicle sales fill the CarCo waterfall.
	2.	If they are insufficient, the unpaid portion â†’ CarCo Deficiency Amount.
â†’ Retained and recorded (no leakage to subordinated parties).
	3.	Next month, when new collections arrive, they first top up that deficiency.

At Issuer level
	1.	Issuer receives what CarCo paid (less deficiency).
	2.	If the received cash + reserves are still enough, note interest and fees are paid as normal.
	3.	If not, the Issuer waterfall authorises drawdown from the Liquidity Reserve to meet senior interest (timely test).

â†’ So investors are paid timely, even if CarCo is momentarily deficient.

â¸»

ğŸ§® 5ï¸âƒ£ How to think about it analytically

Level	Event	Accounting effect	Economic meaning
CarCo	Deficiency retained	Liability to Issuer increases	â€œStill owes Issuer cashâ€
Issuer	Records receivable	Asset = CarCo loan (performing)	â€œIssuer still wholeâ€
